Chalcocite, bornite, chalcopyrite, and pyrite share common bedding and replacement textures, ranging from semi-massive accumulations, to disseminations, to very coarse blebs, and occasionally can form veins. Sulphides commonly mantle and or partially replace clasts in the diamictite. Chalcopyrite, bornite and chalcocite are commonly concentrated in sandy lenses and planar beds within the Ki1.1.1.2 siltstone–sandstone interbed of the basal diamictite. This appears to reflect a local permeability control on the distribution of mineralisation, and is also common in Zambian Ore Shale-hosted deposits. The footwall R4.2 (RFS) sandstone does not generally host significant hypogene mineralisation, as it is located below the redox boundary.

The Kakula copper mineralization displays vertical mineral zonation from chalcopyrite (approximately 35% copper), to bornite (approximately 63% copper) and to chalcocite (approximately 80% copper), with the highest copper grades associated with the siltstone unit consistently characterized by chalcocite-dominant mineralization (see Figure 4 for strip-logs showing typical Kakula-style mineralization in holes DD1021, DD1026 and DD1032).
